    <p>Our <a href="/disc-stack-centrifuge/">disc stack centrifuges</a> turn dirty waste oil into clean, sale-ready product. Whether you collect used motor oil, process black diesel, or re-refine industrial lubricants, Dolphin Centrifuge has a proven system for your operation.</p>

    <h2 id="definition">Definition of Used Oil</h2>
    <p>Used oil is defined as any oil originating in crude oil or petroleum with physical or chemical impurities as contaminants from its use. The United States produces over 2 billion gallons of used oil annually. This oil has considerable value as a heating fuel and for reblending into lube oil after recycling.</p>

    <h3>Difference Between Used Oil and Waste Oil</h3>
    <p>Used oil has mineral-based origins — crude oil or synthetic oil. Used engine oil, transformer oil, and turbine lube oil are examples. Waste oil, on the other hand, has organic origin such as <a href="/wvo-centrifuge-separator/">WVO (waste vegetable oil)</a>, used cooking oil, and yellow grease.</p>

    <h3>Benefits of Used Oil Reclamation</h3>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>Reduce environmental pollution:</strong> Used oil discarded in landfills contaminates groundwater and soil. Recovery prevents this pollution.</li>
      <li><strong>Feedstock for fresh lube oil:</strong> Refined used oil is a feedstock for virgin lubricating oil production — a low-cost, environmentally friendly alternative.</li>
      <li><strong>Heating fuel:</strong> Contaminated used oil has high calorific value and is ideal for industrial building heating.</li>
      <li><strong>Black diesel:</strong> Purified used oil blended with diesel is allowable as fuel for large diesel engines.</li>
    </ul>

    <h2 id="why-centrifuges-for-used-motor-oil">Why Centrifuges for Used Motor Oil</h2>
    <p>Used motor oil contains water, sludge, metals, and carbon particles that must be removed before the oil can be sold, re-refined, or blended into fuel. Traditional heating, settling, and filtration requires large tanks, multiple filter banks, and vacuum distillation — a process that is slow, labor-intensive, and produces inferior results.</p>
    <p>An <a href="/industrial-centrifuge/">industrial oil centrifuge</a> combines most of these recovery steps into one device using highly amplified centrifugal force to separate the oil from water and sediment. A <a href="/disc-stack-centrifuge/">disc stack centrifuge</a> exerts <strong>over 7,000 Gs</strong> of centrifugal force — sufficient to separate all free water and sediment as small as 0.5 microns in a single continuous pass at 10–60 GPM.</p>

    <h3>Separation Efficiency</h3>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>Particle separation:</strong> 0.5 microns for metal particles, 2 microns for non-metal particles</li>
      <li><strong>Water removal:</strong> Simultaneously separates all free water from the oil</li>
      <li><strong>Ash separation:</strong> High centrifugal force separates ash particles that impart the black color to used oil. Flocculants enhance ash separation by solidifying fine particles into larger aggregates.</li>
      <li><strong>Emulsion breaking:</strong> Disc stack centrifuges can extract microparticles that act as nucleoids, assisting in <a href="/waste-oil-emulsion-centrifuge/">emulsion breakdown</a>. Chemically bonded emulsions may need demulsifiers.</li>
    </ul>

    <h3>Advantages Over Settling and Filtration</h3>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>Three-phase separation:</strong> Disc stack centrifuges separate water and sludge simultaneously — filters and gravity settling can only handle sludge.</li>
      <li><strong>Small footprint:</strong> A used oil centrifuge has a fraction of the size of filters and settling tanks for similar capacity.</li>
      <li><strong>Low operating cost:</strong> No filter media required — centrifuges use gravitational force, eliminating media and related labor costs.</li>
      <li><strong>Equipment durability:</strong> Heavy-duty construction allows decades of operation. It is not uncommon for industrial centrifuges to operate for months without shutdown or operator involvement.</li>
      <li><strong>Emulsion separation:</strong> Disc stack centrifuges can break oil-water emulsions by extracting the tiny particles that bind mechanical emulsions.</li>
    </ul>

    <h2 id="waste-oil-recovery">Waste Oil Recovery</h2>
    <p><strong>3-Phase Oil Recovery</strong> — Recover clean, sale-ready oil from collected waste oil streams. Our 3-phase disc stack centrifuges remove water, sludge, and metals down to 1 micron. Processing capacity ranges from 10 to 50 GPM depending on the centrifuge model selected.</p>
    <p>The <a href="/waste-oil-centrifuge/">waste oil centrifuge</a> application is the most popular configuration in our used motor oil lineup. Customers typically see payback in under 12 months through recovered oil sales. Our field experience makes it possible to produce <strong>99.9% clean used oil</strong> from the disc stack centrifuge.</p>

    <h2 id="used-oil-re-refining">Used Oil Re-Refining</h2>
    <p><strong>Re-Refining &amp; Fuel Blending</strong> — Process used motor oil, transmission fluid, and industrial lubricants for re-refining or fuel blending. The centrifuge removes ash, metals, and water to produce a clean feedstock.</p>
    <p>For dedicated re-refining operations, visit our <a href="/used-oil-re-refining-plant-centrifuge/">used oil re-refining centrifuge</a> page for detailed system specifications and process flow diagrams. Capacities range from 10 to 50 GPM.</p>

    <h2 id="black-diesel-cleaning">Black Diesel Cleaning</h2>
    <p><strong>Soot &amp; Carbon Removal</strong> — Clean black diesel and soot-laden fuels for reuse as burner fuel. Purified used oil blended with diesel is also known as black diesel, usable as fuel for large diesel engines. Disc stack centrifuges remove carbon, water, and heavy contaminants at flow rates of 10–30 GPM.</p>
    <p>Learn more about our <a href="/black-diesel-centrifuge/">black diesel centrifuge</a> systems, which are specifically configured for high-carbon-content fuels.</p>

    <h2 id="design-considerations">Design Considerations</h2>
    <p>Specific design considerations apply to used oil centrifuges:</p>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>Acidic material:</strong> Used oil processors use acids to dissolve metals and break emulsions. Low pH requires corrosion-resistant materials — centrifuges with all stainless steel wetted parts are available.</li>
      <li><strong>Chemical injection:</strong> Injection ports upstream of the centrifuge allow adding demulsifiers or flocculants. Metering chemical pumps are available as an option.</li>
      <li><strong>Water phase proportion:</strong> Standard disc stack centrifuges are designed for large volumes of oil with a small proportion of water. Used oil can have relatively high water content — internal centrifuge modifications allow discharge of this larger water volume.</li>
      <li><strong>Special elastomers:</strong> Chemicals or inherent used oil properties may not be compatible with ordinary elastomers. Special elastomers with specific compatibility for the process fluid are available.</li>
    </ul>

